name: 3-plank open wagon
additional_text: Open "plank" wagons are named for the number of planks used in the construction of their sides.

name: LNWR Lady of the Lake class
Four-wheel tank wagon
additional_text: Early four wheel tank wagons are limited to low speeds by their construction and primitive suspension.

name: Peckett Saddle Tank
additional_text: This 0-4-0 saddle tank engine is typical of the many acquired by the GWR from smaller railways during the 1923 grouping of railway companies into the Big Four.

name: Cylindrical tank wagon
additional_text: The GWR's cylindrical tank wagons were built by the Locomotive department, as the iron cylinders used similar techniques to steam engines.

name: Midland Railway 1000 Class
additional_text: The 1000 class is an express locomotive with a three-cylinder arrangement, using a high pressure cylinder inside the frame and two low pressure cylinders on the outside.

name: 5-plank open wagon
additional_text: The 5 plank wagon became one of the common standard types used by the GWR, with thousands built.

name: Iron-framed van
additional_text: This goods van uses an iron frame with a wooden body, making it stronger than earlier wooden-framed vans.

name: LNER ES1
additional_text: The LNER ES1 (ES for Electric Shunter) is designed for hauling heavy freight trains on steep inclines.

name: NER Autocar
additional_text: The NER Autocar is a petrol-electric railcar with a petrol engine driving two electric motors. It was the first use of an internal combustion engine in a railway vehicle.

name: Passenger Carriage
additional_text: In the early 20th century passenger coaches were stretched to greater lengths. This is a typical LNWR design.

name: SECR H Class
additional_text: The South Eastern and Chatham Railway H Class is an 0-4-4T tank engine designed for suburban passenger routes. It was in use until the 1960s.

name: GWR 4400 Prairie Tank
additional_text: The GWR "Small Prairie" tank engines were designed for operating branch lines.

name: GWR "Beaver" flat wagon
additional_text: "Beaver" was the GWR telegraph code for a flat wagon, with an additional letter used to identify the length.

name: GCR Class 9N
additional_text: The GCR 9N (later LNER A5) is a 4-6-2 tank locomotive designed for suburban passenger services.

name: GCR Robinson Class 8K
additional_text: The Robinson 8K is a heavy freight engine that was used as a standard locomotive by the Royal Engineers Railway Operating Division.

name: LNER Gresley K2 "Ragtimer"
additional_text: The Gresley K2 is a freight engine, designed for the GNR which had been using passenger engines to haul goods trains.

name: LNER Raven EF1
additional_text: The LNER EF1 is an early electric freight engine designed for hauling heavy coal trains.

name: LNWR Electric Unit
additional_text: The LNWR built electric multiple units for its inner suburban London routes, sharing track with the Bakerloo and District lines.

name: Six-wheel tank wagon
additional_text: The six wheel tank wagon replaced vans full of milk churns to form the milk trains commonly seen on the GWR.

name: Fowler 4F
additional_text: The Fowler 4F is a development of the earlier Midland 3835 class.

name: GWR Castle Class
additional_text: The Castle Class is a large, powerful express locomotive designed by GWR Chief Mechanical Engineer Charles Collett

name: Fowler 3F "Jinty"
additional_text: The Jinty is a popular tank engine that was built in large quantities. Although small and low powered it is reliable and cheap to run. Jinties were sometimes run in pairs (or more) for working on steep inclines.

name: GWR 5600 Class
additional_text: The 5600 Class is a large tank engine that offers more power and tractive effort than smaller 0-6-0 tank engines, at the expense of greater weight and higher running costs.

name: LMS Hughes Crab
additional_text: The Hughes Crab was named for its distinctive "scuttling" motion, caused by the inclined cylinders.

name: LNER Gresley D49
additional_text: The D49 is a Nigel Gresley designed 4-4-0 locomotive for passenger traffic.

name: GWR King Class
additional_text: The King Class is a larger and more powerful development of the Castle Class, designed for even higher sustained speeds.

name: LMS Fowler 2-6-4T
additional_text: Fowler's 2-6-4T achieved high speeds for a tank engine, and was typically used on longer distance services.

name: Pullman carriage
additional_text: The luxurious Pullman cars were large  and heavy, with many still in use today for restaurant services.

name: GWR Hall Class
additional_text: The GWR 4900 Hall Class set the template for the 4-6-0 mixed traffic locomotive, fast enough for express passenger services with enough tractive effort for freight.

name: LNER Gresley A3
additional_text: The Gresley A3 is a Pacific (4-6-2) locomotive famed for its 100mph+ performance hauling LNER's Flying Scotsman service.

name: GWR 5700 Pannier Tank
additional_text: The 5700 class numbered 863 locomotives, and was ubiquitous across the GWR network.

name: SR Schools Class
additional_text: The Schools class was the most powerful 4-4-0 locomotive produced in  Europe, and the last British locomotive with such a wheel layout.

name: GWR 1400 Class
additional_text: The 1400 class (originally the 4800 class) is an update of an 1868 design with more modern features. Although small, it is capable of high speed.

name: Southern Railway 5-BEL
additional_text: The Southern Railway's "Brighton Belle" used Pullman coaches and remained in use well into the BR era.

name: GWR Railcar
additional_text: The GWR Railcars used AEC bus hardware in a lightweight streamlined body.

name: LMS Stanier Class 5
additional_text: The Stanier Class 5, commonly known as the "Black 5", was a workhorse for the LMS and into the British Rail era. Although intended as a mixed traffic locomotive it was capable of high top speeds.

name: LMS Stanier Jubilee
additional_text: The Jubilee is the counterpart to the Class 5, often called the "Red Stanier" due to its red LMS livery. It was intended for passenger work, with slightly larger diameter driving wheels giving a higher top speed.

name: LMS Stanier 8F
additional_text: The Stanier 8F is a further development of the Class 5, specialised for freight traffic with a 2-8-0 layout.

name: LNER Gresley A4
additional_text: The Gresley A4 is the iconic pinnacle of high-speed British steam, holding numerous speed and power records.

name: LNER Gresley V2
additional_text: The Gresley V2 is derived from the A3 type, adapted to mixed traffic with a shorter boiler, smaller driving wheels and a 2-6-2 layout.

name: GWR 6800 Grange Class
additional_text: The Grange class is a conservative design similar to the Hall class with smaller driving wheels, but proved to be reliable in service.

name: LMS Stanier Coronation
additional_text: The Stanier Coronation briefly held the British speed record for a steam locomotive. In real life, the streamlined casing was only fitted to early examples.

name: Southern Railway 4-COR
additional_text: The Southern Railway was an early pioneer of electrification, with 4-COR units used between London Waterloo and Portsmouth.

name: Southern Railway 2-HAL
additional_text: The 2-HAL (named for 2 units, Half Lavatory) is designed for suburban commuter services.

name: SR Merchant Navy Class
additional_text: The SR Merchant Navy is a large, powerful locomotive with an air-smoothed casing. Bulleid's novel design features proved to be troublesome, and the class was later rebuilt.

name: SR CC Electric
additional_text: With six traction motors, the CC is adept at handling both heavy freight and long passenger trains.

name: SR Bulleid Q1
additional_text: The Q1 was designed for function over form and the most efficient possible use of materials.

name: Hunslet Austerity 0-6-0ST
additional_text: Hunslet's Austerity was designed for shunting duties. It's powerful for its size with good adhesion, but does not run well at higher speeds.

name: WD Austerity 2-8-0
additional_text: Robert Riddles adapted the LMS 8F for low cost and simple construction, resulting in this "austerity" freight locomotive.

name: GWR Modified Hall Class
additional_text: While externally identical to the original Hall class, the Modified Hall was completely new on the inside with many design innovations.

name: GWR County Class
additional_text: The County Class was  Frederick Hawksworth's test of design ideas for a new Pacific. Sadly there was not enough demand for express steam locomotives in the late 1940s.

name: SR West Country Class
additional_text: Bulleid's "Light Pacific" is a smaller and lighter version of the Merchant Navy, capable of operating on more routes.

name: SR Bulleid Leader
additional_text: The Leader was an attempt to make a steam locomotive as easy to operate as a diesel or electric. Complexity, poor reliability and uncomfortably hot cabs caused the project to be scrapped by 1951.

name: LMS Ivatt Class 2
additional_text: The Ivatt Class 2 is a light, low-powered Mogul designed to replace the LMS fleet of 0-6-0 engines.

name: EE 10000
additional_text: The EE 10000 is the first mainline diesel locomotive built in the UK. Two were built for the LMS.

name: LNER Peppercorn A1
additional_text: The Peppercorn A1 is designed for hauling heavy passenger trains of 12 or more carriages. A continuation of the series, 'Tornado', was built in 2008.

name: BR Class 76 (EM1)
additional_text: The Class 76 is an electric freight locomotive designed for the Woodhead Line in the northern Peak District. With high tractive effort, electric traction lent itself to the steep gradients and many tunnels of the line.

name: BR Standard Class 6 "Clan"
additional_text: The Class 6 is a lighter version of the Class 7 "Britannia", with a smaller boiler. Only 10 were produced due to steel shortages.

name: BR Standard Class 7 "Britannia"
additional_text: The Class 7 combines the best features of pre-BR designs from the Big Four, with the aim of reducing maintenance costs.

name: BR Class 08
additional_text: The Class 08 is a diesel-electric shunter that was common across the UK when freight trains were assembled by shunting different consists of wagons. Although slow its low cost and high tractive effort make it a good option for short industrial lines.

name: BR Class 77 (EM2)
additional_text: The Class 77  is a larger version of the earlier Class 76, designed to haul passenger services on the Woodhead Line.

name: BR Class 9F
additional_text: The 9F class included the last steam locomotive ever to be built by British Railways, "Evening Star"

name: EE Class 55 "Deltic"
additional_text: The Class 55 uses two Napier Deltic marine engines to create a high speed express diesel locomotive.

name: Metro-Cammell Class 101
additional_text: The Class 101 has a four speed gearbox with a manual shift. It was exceptionally long-lived, the final examples being retired in December 2003.

name: BR Mk1 carriage
additional_text: The Mk1 carriage combined best practice from the different Big Four carriage designs into a single standard design that could be used across the BR network.

name: BR Mk2 carriage
additional_text: The Mk2 carriage is the second BR carriage design. It was built to be stronger than the Mk1, giving better corrosion resistance and being safer for passengers in an accident.

name: Brush Class 31 "Gurgler"
additional_text: The Class 31 (Brush Type 2) was part of BR's pilot scheme to test replacing steam locmotives with diesel traction. It had many nicknames including "Ped", "Gargoyle" and "Gurgler"

name: EE Class 20 "Chopper"
additional_text: The Class 20 (English Electric Type 1) is a diesel-electric locomotive designed for light freight duties. Due to its simple design it was more reliable than many contemporary locomotives, leading to a large number being built.

name: EE GT3
additional_text: The GT3 was part of a programme to test gas turbine locomotives. It used a conventional steam driving wheel arrangement to keep the design simple.

name: BR Class 42 "Warship"
additional_text: The Class 42 is based on the German V200 design, scaled down to fit the smaller British loading gauge and built under licence by British manufacturers.

name: EE Class 40 "Whistler"
additional_text: Initially unwanted due to the small improvement in performance over the Class 7 Britannia, the Class 40 (English Electric Type 4) found its home on the West Coast Main Line.

name: BR Class 28 "Metrovick"
additional_text: The Class 28 features some unusual design elements, with a two-stroke diesel engine and a "Co-Bo" layout with five axles: three at the front and two at the rear. It was sadly unreliable in use, with engine problems and a tendency for the cab windows to fall out.

name: BR Class 71 (HA)
additional_text: The Class 71 is a mixed-traffic electric locomotive designed to work on the third rail system. It offered a lot of power for a small locomotive, but being confined to third rail power with no auxiliary option limited its usefulness.

name: BRCW Class 26 "Teacup"
additional_text: The Class 26 "Teacup" (so named for its idling sound) was an early Type 2 locomotive, small diesels with engine output between 800 and 1,250 hp.

name: EE Class 23 "Baby Deltic"
additional_text: The Class 23 uses a smaller version of the Napier Deltic engine fitted to the Class 55, leading to its nickname of "Baby Deltic".

name: AEI Class 81 (AL1)
additional_text: Built by Associated Electrical Industries, the Class 81 was British Railways' first AC electric locomotive. Two types were envisioned, but all delivered were geared for 100mph passenger and express freight usage.

name: EE Class 37 "Tractor"
additional_text: The Class 37 (English Electric Type 3) is widely used, especially in Scotland where the high power, low axle load and lack of need for electrification make it ideal for hauling long trains in the Highlands.

name: Sulzer Class 45 "Peak"
additional_text: The Sulzer Peaks served express passenger trains on the Midland Main Line until the introduction of the HST.

name: BRCW Class 33 "Crompton"
additional_text: The Class 33 was built without carriage heating, using the space for an 8 cylinder engine. This meant it was used for tourist-loaded passenger trains in summer, and freight in winter.

name: MC Class 251 "Blue Pullman"
additional_text: The Blue Pullman is an express diesel multiple unit, designed to tempt motorists from their cars with a luxurious inter-city service.

name: Pressed Steel Class 121 "Bubble Car"
additional_text: The "Bubble Car" units saw a long life on branch lines and rural railways. Two six-cylinder AEC or Leyland engines of 150hp each drive the wheels through a mechanical transmission.

name: BR Class 35 "Hymek"
additional_text: The Hymeks were named for their hydraulic transmission. Sadly this also caused their early withdrawal, with BR viewing diesel-hydraulics as non-standard.

name: BR Class 52 "Western"
additional_text: The Class 52 was the most powerful of the Western Region's diesel-hydraulic locomotives, pushing the limits of what 1960s transmission technology could achieve.

name: Sulzer Class 25 "Rat"
additional_text: The Class 25 locomotives became known as "Rats" because they were found all over the British Rail network.

name: Brush Class 47 "Spoon"
additional_text: The Class 47 diesel-electric arose from BR's desire for a lighter Type 4 (over 2000hp) locomotive, without using the diesel-hydraulic technology favoured by the Western Region.

name: Clayton Class 17
additional_text: The Class 17 attempted to solve the problems of visibility from a single cab. It had an unsuccessful life beset by engine reliability problems, and all examples were withdrawn early.

name: BR Class 14 "Teddy Bear"
additional_text: BR envisaged a need  for small diesel locomotives to run short-distance freight trains, but by the end of the 1960s this need had evaporated. The Class 14s were sold to industry, and saw continued use on private railways.

name: BR Class 73 (JB)
additional_text: The Class 73 is a dual-power locomotive, running at full power when connected to a third rail supply but carrying a small diesel engine for running on non-electrified track.

name: BR Class 86 (AL6)
additional_text: The Class 86 (originally AL6) was BR's first standard electric locomotive, incorporating experience from prototypes such as the Class 81.

name: EE Class 50 "Hoover"
additional_text: The Class 50 hauled express services on the West Coast Main Line until electrification, at which point they were used to replace diesel-hydraulic engines in the Western Region.

name: BREL Class 87
additional_text: The Class 87 was a further development of the Class 86 with even more power and performance, serving as the flagship of the British Rail electric fleet.

name: BREL Class 43 HST
additional_text: The Class 43 HST is a high-speed diesel-electric locomotive, also known as the Intercity 125 for its 125mph service speed and intended use on long routes between cities.

name: BR Mk3 carriage
additional_text: The Mk3 carriage is designed for higher speed operation, capable of running at up to 125mph. The first Mk3 carriages were built for the prototype HST.

name: BREL Class 56 "Grid"
additional_text: The Class 56 is designed for heavy freight work. It contains many improvements to the electric drivetrain compared to earlier diesel-electric locomotives, making it more reliable and easier to operate.

name: BREL Class 313
additional_text: The Class 313 is a dual voltage EMU capable of running both on overhead electrified lines and third rail systems.

name: BREL Class 315
additional_text: The Class 315 is the last class of the 1972 standard EMU design, running on 25kV overhead AC power and used for inner suburban services.

name: BREL Class 58 "Bone"
additional_text: The Class 58 used a modular design with replaceable modules mounted to an underframe. It was nicknamed "Bone" after the narrow central section.

name: EMD Class 59
additional_text: The Class 59 is the first US-built locomotive to operate in mainland Great Britain. It is derived from the SD40, with a British cab layout.

name: BREL Class 90
additional_text: The Class 90 is a powerful electric locomotive. Initially used for Intercity express services, several were also used for freight.

name: BREL Class 319
additional_text: The Class 319 is a dual-voltage EMU built for the then-new Thameslink service between Brighton and Bedford.

name: BR Mk4 carriage
additional_text: The Mk4 carriage is a further improvement on the Mk3. It's designed for use with the Class 91 for Intercity 225 services.

name: BREL Class 91
additional_text: The Class 91 is a high speed electric locomotive, designed for Intercity 225 services.

name: Driving Van Trailer
additional_text: This driving van trailer can be used with other electric locomotives, either as a leading or trailing vehicle. It is recommended for use with the Class 91.

name: BREL Class 465 "Networker"
additional_text: The BREL Networker was built by three different companies (ABB, Metro-Cammell and BREL) with minor detail differences between each manufacturer's output.

name: ABB Class 92 "Caravan"
additional_text: The Class 92 was designed to operate services through the Channel Tunnel. It can run on both the Southern Region third rail system and overhead wires.

name: EMD Class 66
additional_text: After the successful introduction of the Class 59, EWS approached GM's Electro-Motive diesel with a huge order of 250 locomotives which would become Class 66.

name: Brush Class 57 "Bodysnatcher"
additional_text: The Class 57 is a re-engineered locomotive using Class 47 bodyshells and parts, giving rise to its "Bodysnatcher" nickname.

name: Alstom Class 67 "Skip"
additional_text: The Class 67 is a high speed freight locomotive designed for mail service. It uses EMD engines, generators and traction motors.

name: Alstom Class 460 "Juniper"
additional_text: The Class 460 was built to replace locomotive-hauled services on the Gatwick Express. It had a short service life, with most units converted to Class 458/5 for suburban use.

name: Bombardier Class 377 "Electrostar"
additional_text: The Class 377 is a dual-voltage EMU, and is a common sight around London and South East England.

name: GE Class 70
additional_text: The General Electric Class 70 is designed with crash safety in mind, hence the bonnet-like structure at each end.

name: Stadler Class 68 "Warskip"
additional_text: The Class 68 is a modern mixed traffic disel locomotive with a powerful 16-cylinder Caterpillar engine.

name: Bombardier Class 170 "Turbostar"
additional_text: The Turbostar is a further development of the BR "Networker" units. It is used for regional and long distance services.

name: Bombardier Class 378 "Capitalstar"
additional_text: The Capitalstar is an electric multiple unit designed specifically for the needs of the London Overground, with longitudinal seating, large amounts of standing room and wide doors for fast loading and unloading.

name: Siemens Class 450 "Desiro"
additional_text: The Class 450 was designed for South West Trains to replace all slam-door stock. The large order meant the Class 450 became the most numerous type of Desiro unit in the UK.

name: Siemens Class 444 "Desiro"
additional_text: The Class 444 is an express variant of the Desiro family, used on services to and from the South Coast. Its high power compared to earlier EMUs required power networks in the third rail region to be upgraded.

name: BREL Class 455
additional_text: The Class 455 is a DC third rail version of British Rail's second generation EMU design. Some units re-used existing carriages from the Class 508, recognisable by the different side profile.

name: BREL Class 456
additional_text: The Class 456 is a two-car EMU used for inner suburban services - either as a single unit for services with low demand or coupled to other Class 456 or 455 units for higher capacity routes.

name: Brush Class 60 "Tug"
additional_text: The Brush Class 60 is a Type 5 diesel, designed for high power and tractive effort to haul heavy freight trains.

name: BR Class 506
additional_text: The Class 506 was built by Metro Cammell and BRCW for the Woodhead Line.

name: BR Class 414 "2 HAP"
additional_text: The Class 414 2 HAP (Half Lavatory, electro-Pneumatic brake) is a Southern Region electric multiple unit, geared for express duties.

name: BR Class 310 AM10
additional_text: The AM10 was the first EMU to be based on the Mk2 carriage bodyshell. They were introduced as part of the West Coast Main Line electrification.

name: BREL Class 421 "4 CIG"
additional_text: The Class 421 4 CIG (Corridor, brIGhton) was a third rail EMU with express gearing, used in the Southern Region. It was based on the Mk1 carriage design.

name: BREL Class 150 "Sprinter"
additional_text: The Sprinter replaced first-generation DMUs. Like other second-generation units it was based on the Mark 3 bodyshell. The name refers to its faster acceleration compared to the units it replaced.

name: Metro-Cammell Class 156 "Super Sprinter"
additional_text: The Class 156 is a member of the Sprinter family designed for longer journeys, with single doors at each end rather than the metro-style doors of the Class 150s.
